{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510508"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:30:51+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:30:51+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11575"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11575","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11575"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.23,0.06,0.04,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4204"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79010"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4204"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11575"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64359"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1865"},{"type":"tags","id":"2058"},{"type":"tags","id":"2468"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4956"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"11637"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5435"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26980"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33093"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33100"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33101"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35071"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35730"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41146"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79010"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man with Down syndrome presents to his General Practitioner with his regular carer. His carer states that the patient has become increasingly agitated in the last two days, and has been becoming violent towards himself and others at the care facility in which he resides. His carer is concerned about the behaviours, although states that he is able to be calmed and redirected easily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient is verbal, and able to engage well in conversation. Previous neuropsychological assessment determined IQ to be 68 (average: 90 - 110). When questioned further, he reports no localising symptoms. His medical history includes myopia, for which he wears corrective spectacles, and a patent ductus arteriosus which was appropriately managed around the time of his birth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, his pulse rate is 85/min, respiratory rate 14/min, blood pressure 152/90mmHg, temperature 38.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 99% on room air. His BMI is 32. He is appropriate and engages well with the doctor whilst being examined. He has poor dentition. His cardiovascular, respiratory and abdominal examinations are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following should be the priority for preventative health activities to engage in?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Encouraging regular dental check-ups","Pharmacological management of blood pressure","Pharmacological management of problem behaviours","Regular vision checks","Evaluation for mental illness"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question tests candidates about the management of adults with intellectual and developmental disabilities, such as Trisomy 21 (Down syndrome). Management of these disabilities is complex and often requires multidisciplinary care input.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile each of the answers is likely to be a good option for preventative healthcare in an adult with an intellectual disability, this patient has evidence of an infection of unknown origin (although most likely of dental origin, given his poor dentition). As such, the acute management and his infection, and ongoing management to improve his dentition through \u003Cstrong\u003Eencouraging regular dental check-ups \u003C/strong\u003Eshould be the priority for this patient. Furthermore, as there is a significant link between periodontal disease and other chronic diseases (e.g. cardiovascular disease), this should be a priority in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are a number of other sequelae which may occur in adults with intellectual disabilities. For instance, Helicobacter pylori gastritis is very common in supported accomodation settings, as faecal/oral transmission is significant. Patients with this condition often present as being acutely unwell, with response behaviours as a result. Additionally, atlanto-axial instability can present with neurogenic claudication, or localised pain, and symptoms of distress. Haematological and lymphoproliferative disorders can also present as patients being acutely unwell, with or without localising signs of infection. Finally, 50% of those with Down Syndrome will have associated Alzheimer\u0027s dementia, although this will usually present more chronically.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile this patient\u0027s blood pressure is elevated, and those with Down Syndrome are at greater risk of cardiovascular disease (as nearly half of those with Down Syndrome have congential heart defects), this should be re-checked at his next visit, to ensure it is not simply a sign consistent with his infection. As such, \u003Cstrong\u003Epharmacological management of his blood pressure\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProblem behaviours such as self-harm are common in those with intellectual disabilities. In this case, as the behaviours are able to be managed with non-pharmacological methods (e.g. re-direction) and no \u003Cstrong\u003Epharmacological management \u003C/strong\u003Eis required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular vision checks\u003C/strong\u003E are important in those with Down Syndrome, especially considering this patient has a prior history of ophthalmic disease. However, this can be encouraged at a later date, when the infection has cleared, and his acute dental disease is more well controlled.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMental illness \u003C/strong\u003E(e.g., depression, anxiety, and obssessive-compulsive disorder) are common in adults with intellectual disabilities. As this patient currently appears calm, and is willing and able to engage in conversation, this could potential be re-visited at a later date.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Adults with developmental disabilities are at risk of periodontal disease, which also predispose to other chronic conditions (e.g. cardiovascular disease).","Regular dental check-ups are crucial for preventing dental infections, which can lead to behavioural changes in individuals with intellectual disabilities."],"references":["Sullivan WF, Berg JM, Bradley E, Cheetham T, Denton R, Heng J, Hennen B, Joyce D, Kelly M, Korossy M, Lunsky Y, McMillan S; Colloquium on Guidelines for the Primary Health Care of Adults with Developmental Disabilities. Primary care of adults with developmental disabilities: Canadian consensus guidelines. Can Fam Physician. 2011 May;57(5):541-53, e154-68. PMID: 21571716; PMCID: PMC3093586. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21571716/","Baldor R. Primary care of the adult with intellectual and developmental disabilities. [Internet] 2024 Dec. UpToDate. Accessed on 13 Jan 2025. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/primary-care-of-the-adult-with-intellectual-and-developmental-disabilities","Wriedt S, Service F, Schmidtmann I, Erbe C. Orthodontic findings in adults with Trisomy 21. Clin Oral Investig. 2024 Jul 30;28(8):456. doi: 10.1007/s00784-024-05846-5. PMID: 39078509; PMCID: PMC11289360. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC11289360/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64359"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11575"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64359","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64359"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-13T13:10:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-13T13:12:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4204"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79010"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"descript